{{Otheruses}}
{{Unreferenced|date=March 2015}}
'''Yakko''' (奴) refers to the [[Edo period]] [[samurai]] [[retainer]] class of [[servants]]. In ancient times, as depicted in the [[Kojiki]], the term "yakko" is believed to have referred to the [[slave]] class{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

== Characteristics ==
{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2015}}
[[File:Yakko-no-Neri ac (8).jpg|thumb|Yakko Furikomi (Kariya City, Aichi Prefecture)]]

Yakko were of the lowest rank among [[samurai retainers]] working in samurai households. They were often disparagingly called "chūgen" (中間) or "orisuke" (折助). The term "yakko" is thought to derive from the ancient [[slave]] system's term "yakko" and "yatsuko" (家つ子), meaning "house child." Notably, "yakko" also has parallels in [[Greek]] and [[Latin]], where terms for "household members" also came to mean "slave"{{Sfn|Kitō|1994|page=217}}.

Yakko were often employed from the second or third sons of [[farmers]] or common [[townspeople]] who could not inherit family occupations. Their work included carrying the baggage of [[samurai]] on outings and performing various other menial tasks{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

The [[uniform]] of yakko, often a [[hanten]] (半纏), bore a large rectangular pattern instead of the family crest of the master. This pattern, called "kuginuki" (釘抜, nail-puller crest), derived from the square shape of a washer. This association led to terms like "yakko-giri" (奴に切る), describing cutting food into larger cube shapes. Cold [[tofu]] served in such shapes is called "hiyayakko" (冷奴){{Sfn|Tsuyutani|1911|loc=「（三十四）奴豆腐」|page=30頁 (コマ番号0017.jp2)}}{{Sfn|Murai|1924|loc=「磯奴豆腐」、「枝豆の奴豆腐」|pages=185-186頁 (コマ番号0113.jp2-0114.jp2)}}; when heated, it becomes "netsuyakko" or "yuyakko"{{Sfn|Tsuyutani|1911|loc=「（九十七）湯奴 」|pages=67−68頁 (コマ番号0035.jp2-)}}.

The "yakko kite" (奴凧), commonly seen during New Year kite-flying, mimics a yakko holding the edges of their hanten's sleeves wide open{{Efn|Some [[ukiyo-e]] from the late Edo period depict people mimicking yakko{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}.}}. The kite's design includes a sleeve-like structure for stability{{Sfn|Akiyama|1986|pages=1362–1365}}.

The term "yakko" also influenced cultural expressions. Male [[performers]] and women from [[brothels]] or [[geisha districts]] often imitated the behaviors of yakko, leading to terms like "○○yakko" being used for [[courtesans]] or [[geisha]], which continue to appear in [[stage names]].

== Yakko in Media ==
{{See also|Processions of the Times}}
Yakko costumes appear in [[kabuki]], [[kabuki dance]], and [[historical parades]]{{Efn|During celebrations for the Showa Emperor's enthronement, historical parades featured yakko in daimyō processions{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「時代風俗行列」|page= (コマ番号0122.jp2)}} and palanquin bearers{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「元氣な奴さん /  大久保彦左衞門」|page= (コマ番号0124.jp2)}}.}}. The costume includes a padded hanten with a "kuginuki" crest, a wide round belt (maruguke), and visible [[fundoshi]]{{Anchors|Fundoshi|Sagari}} to show non-samurai status{{Sfn|Toyokuni|1860|loc=「一世一代岸沢古式部 § 花見帰の供奴」}}. Black or dark-colored [[tabi]] are commonly worn{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}. A lively [[端唄]] titled "Yakko-san" captures their spirit{{Sfn|Sakai|1923|page=1|ws=『竹保流[[尺八]]音譜著名端唄全集』}}{{Sfn|Yoshida|1936|page=46|ws=『尺八練習百曲集』}}.

<gallery>
NDL-DC 1311927 01-Utagawa Kunisada-奴凧平 市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助-文久2-crd.jpg|[[Ukiyo-e]] "Yakko Takobei" (奴凧平) (from 'Toyokuni Album', late Edo period){{Efn|In the ukiyo-e, kabuki actor [[Ichikawa Shisō]] mimics a yakko kite, suspended for an acrobatic performance.}}
Image:Red-faced dancers after 2006 Aizu parade.JPG|Participant dressed as yakko in a historical parade, face painted red as a symbol of strength. (Daimyō procession, Aizuwakamatsu City)
Image:Odori023.jpg|Participant portraying [[Watōnai]] from {{ill|The Battles of Coxinga|ja|国性爺合戦}}. (Tiger Dance, Yokosuka City)
</gallery>

