The {{ill|uniform|ja|制服}} of yakko, often a {{ill|hanten|ja|半纏}}, bore a large rectangular pattern instead of the family crest of the master. This pattern, called "kuginuki" (釘抜, nail-puller crest), derived from the square shape of a washer. This association led to terms like "yakko-giri" (奴に切る), describing cutting food into larger cube shapes. Cold {{ill|tofu|ja|豆腐}} served in such shapes is called "hiyayakko" (冷奴){{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（三十四）奴豆腐」|page=30頁 (コマ番号0017.jp2)}}{{Sfn|Murai|1924|loc=「磯奴豆腐」、「枝豆の奴豆腐」|pages=185-186頁 (コマ番号0pp3.jp2-0pp4.jp2)}}; when heated, it becomes "netsuyakko" or "yuyakko"{{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（九十七）湯奴 」|pages=67−68頁 (コマ番号0035.jp2-)}}.

The "yakko kite" ({{ill|Yakko kite|ja|奴凧}}), commonly seen during New Year kite-flying, mimics a yakko holding the edges of their hanten's sleeves wide open{{Efn|Some {{ill|ukiyo-e|ja|浮世絵}} from the late Edo period depict people mimicking yakko{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}.}}. The kite's design includes a sleeve-like structure for stability{{Sfn|Akiyama|1986|pages=1362–1365}}.

The term "yakko" also influenced cultural expressions. Male {{ill|performers|ja|芸人}} and women from {{ill|brothels|ja|遊廓}} or {{ill|Hanamachi|lt=geisha districts|ja|花柳界}} often imitated the behaviors of yakko, leading to terms like "○○yakko" being used for {{ill|courtesans|ja|遊女}} or {{ill|geisha|ja|芸者}}, which continue to appear[[Category:pp to pp]] in {{ill|stage names|ja|芸名}}.

== Yakko in Media ==
{{See also|historical reenactment parade}}

Yakko costumes appear[[Category:pp to pp]] in {{ill|kabuki|ja|歌舞伎}}, {{ill|kabuki dance|ja|歌舞伎舞踊}}, and {{ill|Historical reenactment parade|lt=historical parades|ja|時代行列}} {{Efn|During celebrations for the Showa Emperor's enthronement, historical parades featured yakko in daimyō processions{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「時代風俗行列」|page= (コマ番号0122.jp2)}} and palanquin bearers{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「元氣な奴さん /  大久保彦左衞門」|page= (コマ番号0124.jp2)}}.}}. The costume includes a padded hanten with a "kuginuki" crest, a wide round belt (maruguke), and visible {{ill|fundoshi|ja|褌}}{{Anchors|Fundoshi|Sagari}} to show non-samurai status{{Sfn|Toyokuni|1860|loc=「一世一代岸沢古式部 § 花見帰の供奴」}}. Black or dark-colored {{ill|tabi|ja|足袋}} are commonly worn{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}. A lively {{ill|端唄|ja|端唄}} titled "Yakko-san" captures their spirit{{Sfn|Sakai|1923|page=1|ws=『竹保流[[尺八]]音譜著名端唄全集』}}{{Sfn|Yoshida|1936|page=46|ws=『尺八練習百曲集』}}.

