'''Yakko''' (奴) refers to the [[Edo period]] [[samurai]] [[retainer]] class of [[servants]]. In ancient times, as depicted in the [[Kojiki]], the term "yakko" is believed to have referred to the [[slave]] class{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

== Characteristics ==
{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2015}}
[[File:Yakko-no-Neri ac (8).jpg|thumb|Yakko Furikomi (Kariya City, Aichi Prefecture)]]

Yakko were of the lowest rank among {{ill|samurai retainers|ja|武家奉公人|12=draft}} working in samurai households. They were often disparagingly called "chūgen" ({{ill|Chūgen|ja|中間|12=draft}}) or "orisuke" ({{ill|Orisuke|ja|折助|12=draft}}). The term "yakko" is thought to derive from the ancient {{ill|slave|ja|奴隷|12=draft}} system's term "yakko" and "yatsuko" (家つ子), meaning "house child." Notably, "yakko" also has parallels in [[Greek]] and [[Latin]], where terms for "household members" also came to mean "slave"{{Sfn|Kitō|1994|page=217}}.

Yakko were often employed from the second or third sons of {{ill|farmers|ja|農民|12=draft}} or common {{ill|Chōnin|lt=townspeople|ja|町人|12=draft}} who could not inherit family occupations. Their work included carrying the baggage of {{ill|samurai|ja|武士|12=draft}} on outings and performing various other menial tasks{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

The {{ill|uniform|ja|制服|12=draft}} of yakko, often a {{ill|hanten|ja|半纏|12=draft}}, bore a large rectangular pattern instead of the family crest of the master. This pattern, called "kuginuki" (釘抜, nail-puller crest), derived from the square shape of a washer. This association led to terms like "yakko-giri" (奴に切る), describing cutting food into larger cube shapes. Cold {{ill|tofu|ja|豆腐|12=draft}} served in such shapes is called "hiyayakko" (冷奴){{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（三十四）奴豆腐」|page=30頁 (コマ番号0017.jp2)}}{{Sfn|Murai|1924|loc=「磯奴豆腐」、「枝豆の奴豆腐」|pages=185-186頁 (コマ番号0pp3.jp2-0pp4.jp2)}}; when heated, it becomes "netsuyakko" or "yuyakko"{{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（九十七）湯奴 」|pages=67−68頁 (コマ番号0035.jp2-)}}.

The "yakko kite" ({{ill|Yakko kite|ja|奴凧|12=draft}}), commonly seen during New Year kite-flying, mimics a yakko holding the edges of their hanten's sleeves wide open{{Efn|Some {{ill|ukiyo-e|ja|浮世絵|12=draft}} from the late Edo period depict people mimicking yakko{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}.}}. The kite's design includes a sleeve-like structure for stability{{Sfn|Akiyama|1986|pages=1362–1365}}.

The term "yakko" also influenced cultural expressions. Male {{ill|performers|ja|芸人|12=draft}} and women from {{ill|brothels|ja|遊廓|12=draft}} or {{ill|Hanamachi|lt=geisha districts|ja|花柳界|12=draft}} often imitated the behaviors of yakko, leading to terms like "○○yakko" being used for {{ill|courtesans|ja|遊女|12=draft}} or {{ill|geisha|ja|芸者|12=draft}}, which continue to appear in {{ill|stage names|ja|芸名|12=draft}}.

