Yakko costumes appear in {{ill|kabuki|ja|歌舞伎|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|kabuki dance|ja|歌舞伎舞踊|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Historical reenactment parade|lt=historical parades|ja|時代行列|12=draft|12=draft}} {{Efn|During celebrations for the Showa Emperor's enthronement, historical parades featured yakko in daimyō processions{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「時代風俗行列」|page= (コマ番号0122.jp2)}} and palanquin bearers{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「元氣な奴さん /  大久保彦左衞門」|page= (コマ番号0124.jp2)}}.}}. The costume includes a padded hanten with a "kuginuki" crest, a wide round belt (maruguke), and visible {{ill|fundoshi|ja|褌|12=draft|12=draft}}{{Anchors|Fundoshi|Sagari}} to show non-samurai status{{Sfn|Toyokuni|1860|loc=「一世一代岸沢古式部 § 花見帰の供奴」}}. Black or dark-colored {{ill|tabi|ja|足袋|12=draft|12=draft}} are commonly worn{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}. A lively {{ill|端唄|ja|端唄|12=draft|12=draft}} titled "Yakko-san" captures their spirit{{Sfn|Sakai|1923|page=1|ws=『竹保流[[尺八]]音譜著名端唄全集』}}{{Sfn|Yoshida|1936|page=46|ws=『尺八練習百曲集』}}.

