{{Otheruses}}

{{Unreferenced|date=March 2015}}
'''Yakko''' (奴) refers to the [[Edo period]] [[samurai]] [[retainer]] class of [[servants]]. In ancient times, as depicted in the [[Kojiki]], the term "yakko" is believed to have referred to the [[slave]] class{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

== Characteristics ==
{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2015}}
[[File:Yakko-no-Neri ac (8).jpg|thumb|Yakko Furikomi (Kariya City, Aichi Prefecture)]]

Yakko were of the lowest Rank among {{ill|samurai retainers|ja|武家奉公人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/samurai retainers|qq=}} working in samurai households. They were often disparagingly called "chūgen" ({{ill|Chūgen|ja|中間|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūgen|qq=}}) or "orisuke" ({{ill|Orisuke|ja|折助|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Orisuke|qq=}}). The term "yakko" is thought to derive from the ancient {{ill|slave|ja|奴隷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/slave|qq=}} system's term "yakko" and "yatsuko" (家つ子), meaning "house child." Notably, "yakko" also has parallels in [[Greek]] and [[Latin]], where terms for "household members" also came to mean "slave"{{Sfn|Kitō|1994|page=217}}.

Yakko were often employed from the second or third sons of [[:en:Peasant|farmers]] or common [[:en:Chōnin|townspeople]] who could not inherit family occupations. Their work included carrying the baggage of {{ill|samurai|ja|武士|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/samurai|qq=}} on outings and performing various other menial tasks{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}.

The [[:en:Uniform|uniform]] of yakko, often a {{ill|hanten|ja|半纏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hanten|qq=}}, bore a large rectangular pattern instead of the family crest of the master. This pattern, called "kuginuki" (釘抜, nail-puller crest), derived from the square shape of a washer. This association led to terms like "yakko-giri" (奴に切る), describing cutting food into larger cube shapes. Cold [[:en:Tofu|tofu]] served in such shapes is called "hiyayakko" (冷奴){{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（三十四）奴豆腐」|page=30頁 (コマ番号0017.jp2)}}{{Sfn|Murai|1924|loc=「磯奴豆腐」、「枝豆の奴豆腐」|pages=185-186頁 (コマ番号0pp3.jp2-0pp4.jp2)}}; when heated, it becomes "netsuyakko" or "yuyakko"{{Sfn|Tsuyutani|19pp|loc=「（九十七）湯奴 」|pages=67−68頁 (コマ番号0035.jp2-)}}.

The "yakko kite" ({{ill|Yakko kite|ja|奴凧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yakko kite|qq=}}), commonly seen during New Year kite-flying, mimics a yakko holding the edges of their hanten's sleeves wide open{{Efn|Some [[:en:Ukiyo-e|ukiyo-e]] from the late Edo period depict people mimicking yakko{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}.}}. The kite's design includes a sleeve-like structure for stability{{Sfn|Akiyama|1986|pages=1362–1365}}.

The term "yakko" also influenced cultural expressions. Male {{ill|performers|ja|芸人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/performers|qq=}} and women from [[:en:Yūkaku|brothels]] or {{ill|Hanamachi|lt=geisha districts|ja|花柳界|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanamachi|qq=}} often imitated the behaviors of yakko, leading to terms like "○○yakko" being used for {{ill|courtesans|ja|遊女|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/courtesans|qq=}} or {{ill|geisha|ja|芸者|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/geisha|qq=}}, which continue to appear in [[:en:Stage name|stage names]].

== Yakko in Media ==
{{See also|historical reenactment parade}}

Yakko costumes appear in [[:en:Kabuki|kabuki]], [[:en:Shosagoto|kabuki dance]], and {{ill|Historical reenactment parade|lt=historical parades|ja|時代行列|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Historical reenactment parade|qq=}} {{Efn|During celebrations for the Showa Emperor's enthronement, historical parades featured yakko in daimyō processions{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「時代風俗行列」|page= (コマ番号0122.jp2)}} and palanquin bearers{{Sfn|Kyōshinsya|1929|loc=「元氣な奴さん /  大久保彦左衞門」|page= (コマ番号0124.jp2)}}.}}. The costume includes a padded hanten with a "kuginuki" crest, a wide round belt (maruguke), and visible {{ill|fundoshi|ja|褌|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/fundoshi|qq=}}{{Anchors|Fundoshi|Sagari}} to show non-samurai status{{Sfn|Toyokuni|1860|loc=「一世一代岸沢古式部 § 花見帰の供奴」}}. Black or dark-colored [[:en:Tabi|tabi]] are commonly worn{{Sfn|Utagawa|1862|loc=「奴凧平（市川市蔵・夢想兵衛 下り中村鶴助）」2枚組の右片}}. A lively {{ill|端唄|ja|端唄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/端唄|qq=}} titled "Yakko-san" captures their spirit{{Sfn|Sakai|1923|page=1|ws=『竹保流[[尺八]]音譜著名端唄全集』}}{{Sfn|Yoshida|1936|page=46|ws=『尺八練習百曲集』}}.

